===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `gted` (Graphical Text Editor) yek virayeshgare matni grafiki ast. Ba in dastoor mitoonid file-haye matni ro baz konid, taghir bedid, va zakhire konid.  In command baraye karbarani ke tarjih midand az yek muhit grafiki baraye virayesh matn estefade konand mofid ast.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `gted filename` --> 📝 Baz kardane yek file ba name `filename`. Agar file vojood nadashte bashad, yek file jadid sakhte mishavad.
    🔹 `gted` --> 💻 Baz kardane virayeshgar bedoone baz kardane file khass. Shoma mitoonid az menu-ye virayeshgar file-haye digar ro baz konid.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ gted myfile.txt

    🔹 Baz kardane file-e "myfile.txt" dar virayeshgar.

    $ gted

    🔹 Baz kardane virayeshgar bedoone file.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ gted newfile.txt

    🔹 Agar "newfile.txt" vojood nadashte bashad, yek file jadid ba hamin name sakhte mishavad va dar virayeshgar baz mishavad.  Shoma mitoonid matn ro vared konid va file ro zakhire konid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `gted` (Graphical Text Editor) command is a graphical text editor. You can use it to open, edit, and save text files. This command is useful for users who prefer a graphical environment for text editing.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `gted filename` --> 📝 Opens a file named `filename`. If the file does not exist, a new file is created.
    🔹 `gted` --> 💻 Opens the editor without opening a specific file. You can open other files from the editor's menu.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ gted myfile.txt

    🔹 Opens the file "myfile.txt" in the editor.

    $ gted

    🔹 Opens the editor without a file.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ gted newfile.txt

    🔹 If "newfile.txt" does not exist, a new file with this name is created and opened in the editor. You can enter text and save the file.

